Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the earthquake, tsunami, and Japanese nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates substantial profits and involves a low but explosive risk.
However, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with ordinarily harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of the cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In the case of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of housing values, combined with design flaws in derivatives and repurchase markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
While the underlying risks arise outside of the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgages for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck ensured that the systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repurchase agreements – filed for bankruptcy, causing a freeze in credit markets for several weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, workers' teams valiantly attempt to stop the radiation leaks.
However, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures over the same errors that remain active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want yen risk, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If a currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bonds or mortgage debts, against cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or buy back, n.d.).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that simple financial tremors can significantly affect them.
Some institutions may then find themselves unable to obtain funding through repos, as happened in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually, derivative transactions or repos are not particularly blameworthy.
Each separately transfers risk legitimately to those better able to bear it, or enables financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can blow up the financial system due to its design flaws.
Still today, about 70% of the liabilities of major American financial companies consists of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivative contracts or repos with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its regular creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate when, with just a little more time, the company could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos end up at the front of the repayment queue in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to promote market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be paid back, one way or another.
Certainly.
Other financial actors must take on more risk because the exemptions for derivative players and repos place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect other investors to have an interest in promoting greater market discipline.
But the next actor in line is too often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions. Yet, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The US Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank bill.
But it did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit events derivatives, ndt) did not receive preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist on their counterparties being adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk associated with ultra-low capitalizations when it essentially involved American government money; they would be less likely to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives the risks of Fukushima-type disasters and the risks associated with derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are stark, causing a slowdown in an industry already grappling with security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and contempt but, when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, allowing the financial sector to control its own destiny with minimal legislative oversight.
Regarding the Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami risks through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of keeping fuel rods cool even in the event of a total electrical power supply failure.
However, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damages that the priority of derivatives and repos in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are developed, requiring that final users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for the major financial institutions.
It seems we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully shift the risk related to their decisions onto investors in derivatives and repos when they engage in transactions with financial institutions that are systemically important.
Instead, we survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
